  "market_context": "Nasdaq daily chart showing a sequence of bullish days with aggressive displacement higher. The analyst is walking through how to mark out previous day high/low across consecutive days to establish daily bias and identify drawn liquidity targets.",
  "key_observation": "When price aggressively displaces over previous day high and closes above it, the bias remains bullish and previous day high becomes the drawn liquidity to be taken again on the following day. Each successive close over PDH continues the bullish anticipation.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Establish framework — use displacement (or lack thereof) over PDH/PDL to determine daily bias and drawn liquidity.",
    "Step 2: Note the rule — failure to displace over PDH frames a downward bias toward PDL; failure to displace below PDL frames an upward bias toward PDH.",
    "Step 3: Set lookback to three days back from the current day to mark out the relevant previous day highs and lows.",
    "Step 4: On the Nasdaq daily chart, identify aggressive displacement higher and anticipate PDH being taken.",
    "Step 5: Observe day one — price takes previous day high and closes over it, so anticipate PDH being taken again next day.",
    "Step 6: Observe next day — price displaces over the fair value gap and over PDH, again closing bullish; continue anticipating PDH on the following day.",
    "Step 7: Continue marking PDH each successive day; as long as price closes over PDH, maintain the bullish bias and target the next PDH.",
    "Step 8: Transition — when a daily candle closes bearish and reaches into a daily fair value gap, shift bias to look for previous day low instead."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Marking PDH/PDL over a three-day lookback and tracking displacement vs failure to displace gives a clear, repeatable daily bias framework. Continued closes over PDH justify continued bullish targeting; a bearish close into a daily FVG signals a bias flip toward PDL.",
